did.abstract:
Pamela Burton & Company, an internationally recognized and award-winning landscape architecture firm, has maintained a collection of archives spanning nearly forty-five years of design work. In 1975, Pamela Burton established the company in Santa Monica, California, where the firm has remained ever since. Pamela Burton & Company works in a variety of project typologies and scales, including residential, large-scale residential, commercial, institutional, and municipal. The goal has always been to integrate and harmonize the disciplines of landscape, architecture, and art in a site's cultural and physical environment, while being committed to sustainable design.
The archival collection contains both physical and digital material that reveal Pamela Burton & Company's design processes and procedures, project documentation, and firm recognition.

bioghist.head: Biographical History
bioghist.p: Pamela Burton & Company, an internationally recognized and award-winning landscape architecture firm, has maintained a collection of archives spanning nearly forty-five years of design work. In 1975, Pamela Burton established the company in Santa Monica, California, where the firm has remained ever since. Pamela Burton & Company works in a variety of project typologies and scales, including residential, large-scale residential, commercial, institutional, and municipal. The goal has always been to integrate and harmonize the disciplines of landscape, architecture, and art in a site's cultural and physical environment, while being committed to sustainable design. Pamela Burton & Company continues to create comprehensive landscape architecture design styles for both private and public spaces around the world.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p:
The physical part of the collection includes project rolls of drawings and construction documents; project booklets of presentations and site imagery; project binders of proposals and contracts; slide films of project photography and Pamela Burton's academic research; publications of books and articles about the firm and Pamela Burton; Pamela Burton's project composition notebooks; three-dimensional scale models; and Pamela Burton's personal journals. This collection of hand-drawn and printed material presents all aspects of the firm's projects, from preliminary concepts, revisions, and sketches, to final completion. The work produced over more than four decades displays Pamela Burton's design philosophy and passion, as well as that of all of the team members collectively.
The digital portion of the collection is a digitized copy of some of the physical media mentioned above. The digital material includes scans of sketches, diagrams, drawings, construction documents, surveys, and maps. The significant details of most projects have been scanned into the computer as digital files.
The wide assortment of material in this collection demonstrate the evolution of landscape architecture design practice, methodology, and technology throughout the years. In particular, from the 1970s to the early 2000s, the collection exemplifies the crucial shift of design work produced by hand into the display of work through computer-aided design.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: These are 11"x17" bound presentation booklets made as overviews for PB&Co projects. The hand-drawn and/or printed material classified as a booklet can be any of the following: 11"x17" presentation booklets, architectural drawings, construction documents, sketches, plant imagery and information, reference imagery, research, site photographs and documentation, articles, meeting notes, and project correspondence. Some projects have only one booklet, while others have several. The selected project booklets in this archive range from projects beginning in the early 1980s through ones beginning in 2012.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: These are slides used for both PB&Co projects as well as other types of research conducted by Pamela Burton. Project slides were used for site photography and documentation. Research slides can refer to any of the following work that Pamela Burton produced, documented, or was influenced by in design: college course teaching, lectures, seminars, symposiums, conferences, exhibitions, competitions, graduate schoolwork, career beginnings, design element influences, landscape architect/landscape architecture influences, architect/architecture influences, artist/art influences, and travel/international landscape influences. Some projects and subjects have just a few slides, while others have many.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: These are Pamela Burton's active-project working notebooks for office use. Each notebook consists of notes and information regarding day-by-day work and planning, including: schedules, meetings, contact information, concepts, diagrams, drawings, sketches, and research.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: These files are scans of original project roll material of PB&Co projects that were digitized by PB&Co, and which span the entirety of Burton's career. Each project roll consists of any of the following: construction documents, architectural drawings, sketches, photographs, permits, surveys, and maps. Project rolls vary in size and scope. They range from the late 1970s through the mid-2010s. The older project rolls were drawn by hand and the newer project rolls were created using Computer Aided Design (CAD) software. As the PGB digital archive was being created, PB&Co selected and scanned material based on what they felt was representative of their landscape design.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The files are arranged according to project type: Commercial, Institutional, Residential, Large Scale Residential, Miscellaneous, Municipal. The files are further arranged according to project name.
Please refer to the Digital File Naming Conventions pdf attached to this finding aid for a detailed explanation of the file directory hierarchy and structure of each Project Roll.
